INSERT INTO `blog` (`id`, `date`, `title`, `image`, `short_desc`, `description`, `url`) VALUES
(1, '2025-07-08', 'What Is Hemato-Oncology? Understanding Blood Cancers', 'blog1.jpg', 'Our thoughts frequently turn to the more well-known types of cancer, such as lung, colon, or breast cancer.', '<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Our thoughts frequently turn to the more well-known types of cancer, such as lung, colon, or breast cancer. On the other hand, blood cancers are frequently more complicated and just as serious. Hemato-oncology is the medical specialty that focuses on treating these kinds of cancers. The diagnosis, treatment, and prevention of blood-related cancers, including leukemia, lymphoma, and multiple myeloma, are the main goals of this specialty area of medicine.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Dr. Amit Badola</strong>, a&nbsp;renowned medical and hemato oncologist offers patients battling these difficult conditions compassionate care and state-of-the-art treatment options.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">We&apos;ll delve deeply into the definition of hemato-oncology, including the different kinds of blood cancers, their causes, and symptoms, available&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(44, 130, 201);\"><a href=\"https://drbadolacancercare.com/contact\"><strong>blood cancer treatment</strong></a></span><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">&nbsp;options, and the importance of early diagnosis.</span></p>\r\n<h2 style=\'margin: 8pt 0cm 4pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 21px; font-family: \"Aptos Display\", sans-serif; color: rgb(15, 71, 97); font-weight: normal;\'><br><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 20px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>What is Hemato-Oncology?</strong></span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">The combination of oncology (the study of cancer) and hematology (the study of blood disorders) is known as hemato-oncology. Cancers that start in the tissues that form blood, such as the lymphatic and bone marrow, can be diagnosed and treated by specialists in this field.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Hemato-oncology&apos;s complexity stems from its multidimensionality. Blood cancers can impact the entire immune and circulatory systems, not just one organ or tissue. These cancers can spread quickly and have an immediate effect on general health because blood flows throughout the body.</span></p>\r\n<h2 style=\'margin: 8pt 0cm 4pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 21px; font-family: \"Aptos Display\", sans-serif; color: rgb(15, 71, 97); font-weight: normal;\'><br><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 20px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Types of Blood Cancers</strong></span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">There are three primary types of blood cancers:</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>1. Leukemia</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">The soft, spongy bone marrow, which produces blood cells, is where leukemia starts. The body produces aberrant white blood cells as a result, eventually pushing out healthy cells. Leukemia affects both children and adults and can be either acute (growing quickly) or chronic (growing slowly).</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>2. Lymphoma</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">The lymphatic system, an essential component of the immune system, is where lymphoma starts. White blood cells called lymphocytes are impacted by this kind of cancer. Hodgkin lymphoma and non-Hodgkin lymphoma are the two primary varieties. Both can vary widely in their level of aggression and have distinct subtypes.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>3. Multiple Myeloma</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">White blood cells called plasma cells, which produce antibodies to fight infections, are where this cancer develops. The accumulation of cancerous plasma cells in the bone marrow due to multiple myeloma pushes out healthy blood cells.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Each of these cancers requires a specialized&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(44, 130, 201);\"><a href=\"https://drbadolacancercare.com/typeofcancer/blood-cancer\"><strong>blood cancer treatment</strong></a></span><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">&nbsp;approach, which, based on the patient&apos;s condition, age, and overall health, may involve a mix of therapies.</span></p>\r\n<h2 style=\'margin: 8pt 0cm 4pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 21px; font-family: \"Aptos Display\", sans-serif; color: rgb(15, 71, 97); font-weight: normal;\'><br><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 20px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>What Causes Blood Cancers?</strong></span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Genetic mutations in blood cell DNA are typically the cause of blood cancers. Blood cancers are linked to a number of risk factors, though the precise cause of these mutations isn&apos;t always known:</span></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: disc; list-style-position: inside;\">\r\n    <li style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.15; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Age:</strong> Particularly for multiple myeloma and certain leukemias, the risk rises with age.</li>\r\n    <li style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.15; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Family history:</strong> An increased risk of blood cancer may result from a family history of the disease.</li>\r\n    <li style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.15; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Radiation exposure:</strong> Long-term or severe radiation exposure can cause mutations that can result in cancer.</li>\r\n    <li style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.15; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Exposure to chemicals:</strong> Blood cancers have been connected to specific chemicals, such as benzene, which are frequently found in industrial settings.</li>\r\n    <li style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.15; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Immune system suppression:</strong> Organ transplant recipients and others with compromised immune systems are particularly vulnerable.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2 style=\'margin: 8pt 0cm 4pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 21px; font-family: \"Aptos Display\", sans-serif; color: rgb(15, 71, 97); font-weight: normal;\'><br><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 20px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Symptoms of Blood Cancers</strong></span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Blood cancer symptoms are frequently mild and can be confused with those of other diseases. Typical signs and symptoms include:</span></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: disc; list-style-position: inside;\">\r\n    <li style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.15; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Persistent fatigue and weakness</li>\r\n    <li style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.15; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Frequent infections</li>\r\n    <li style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.15; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Unexplained weight loss</li>\r\n    <li style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.15; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Swollen lymph nodes</li>\r\n    <li style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.15; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Easy bruising or bleeding</li>\r\n    <li style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.15; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Bone pain or tenderness</li>\r\n    <li style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.15; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Fever or chills</li>\r\n    <li style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.15; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Night sweats</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">You should see a specialist right away if you or someone you know is exhibiting any of these symptoms. An early diagnosis can significantly impact the course of&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(44, 130, 201);\"><a href=\"https://drbadolacancercare.com/contact\"><strong>blood cancer treatment</strong></a></span><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">.</span></p>\r\n<h2 style=\'margin: 8pt 0cm 4pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 21px; font-family: \"Aptos Display\", sans-serif; color: rgb(15, 71, 97); font-weight: normal;\'><br><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 20px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Diagnostic Tools in Hemato-Oncology</strong></span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Advanced imaging, laboratory testing, and physical examinations are all used to diagnose blood cancer:</span></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: disc; list-style-position: inside;\">\r\n    <li style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.15; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Blood tests:</strong> White, red, and platelet counts can all be abnormally detected with the use of a complete blood count (CBC).</li>\r\n    <li style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.15; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Bone marrow biopsy:</strong> Involves taking a tiny sample of bone marrow and testing it for cancerous cells.</li>\r\n    <li style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.15; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Lymph node biopsy:</strong> Useful in diagnosing lymphoma.</li>\r\n    <li style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.15; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Imaging tests:</strong> MRIs, PET scans, and CT scans are used to determine the extent and spread of cancer.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">These days, genetic profiling and molecular testing are also frequently utilized to help customize&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(44, 130, 201);\"><a href=\"https://drbadolacancercare.com/contact\"><strong>blood cancer treatment</strong></a></span><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">&nbsp;more efficiently to the distinct genetic composition of every patient.</span></p>\r\n<h2 style=\'margin: 8pt 0cm 4pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 21px; font-family: \"Aptos Display\", sans-serif; color: rgb(15, 71, 97); font-weight: normal;\'><br><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 20px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Treatment Options for Blood Cancers</strong></span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">In recent years, blood cancer treatment has changed dramatically. Patients can now choose from a variety of treatments, such as:</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>1. Chemotherapy</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Chemotherapy kills cancer cells that divide quickly by using strong medications. For many blood cancers, especially leukemia, it&apos;s frequently the first line of treatment.<br></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>2. Radiation Therapy</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">This technique targets and destroys cancer cells using high-energy radiation. In cases of lymphoma, it is utilized more frequently.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>3. Targeted Therapy</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">The purpose of targeted medications is to disrupt particular molecules that are essential to the growth and survival of cancer cells. Compared to conventional chemotherapy, these treatments are frequently less harmful.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>4. Immunotherapy</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Immunotherapy strengthens the body&apos;s defenses against cancer. An immunotherapy called CAR T-cell therapy has demonstrated great promise in the treatment of some forms of refractory lymphoma and leukemia.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>5. Bone Marrow or Stem Cell Transplant</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Through this process, healthy cells from the patient or a donor are used to replace the diseased bone marrow. When alternative therapies have failed, it is taken into consideration.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><br><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">It&rsquo;s important to note that the ideal&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(44, 130, 201);\"><a href=\"https://drbadolacancercare.com/contact\"><strong>blood cancer treatment</strong></a></span><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">&nbsp;plan depends on a multitude of factors &mdash; the patient&apos;s age, general health, cancer type and stage, and reaction to previous treatments. To evaluate the efficacy and make necessary modifications, routine monitoring and follow-ups are essential.</span></p>\r\n<h2 style=\'margin: 8pt 0cm 4pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 21px; font-family: \"Aptos Display\", sans-serif; color: rgb(15, 71, 97); font-weight: normal;\'><br><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 20px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Living with and Beyond Blood Cancer</strong></span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Many blood cancer patients now lead longer, healthier lives as a result of medical advancements. Recovery depends heavily on supportive care, which includes rehabilitation, mental health support, and nutritional counseling. Joining support groups, staying active, and keeping lines of communication open with their medical team are all advised for patients.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;Fear of recurrence, long-term side effects, and emotional exhaustion are some of the difficulties that come with being a survivor. To successfully navigate this phase, a thorough, patient-centered care plan is necessary.</span></p>\r\n<h2 style=\'margin: 8pt 0cm 4pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 21px; font-family: \"Aptos Display\", sans-serif; color: rgb(15, 71, 97); font-weight: normal;\'><br><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 20px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Why Choose a Specialist in Hemato-Oncology?</strong></span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Selecting a committed hemato-oncologist guarantees that you will be treated by a professional who is knowledgeable about the disease&apos;s molecular causes as well as the subtleties of&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(44, 130, 201);\"><a href=\"https://drbadolacancercare.com/contact\"><strong>blood cancer treatment</strong></a></span><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 16px; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(44, 130, 201);\"><a href=\"https://drbadolacancercare.com/\"><strong>Dr. Amit Badola</strong></a></span><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 18px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">&nbsp;offers not only medical knowledge but also compassion and support at every step of the treatment process thanks to his vast clinical experience and patient-first philosophy. Individualized care plans that address the illness and the person behind the diagnosis are provided to patients and their families under his direction.</span></p>\r\n<h2 style=\'margin: 8pt 0cm 4pt; line-height: 1.15; font-size: 21px; font-family: \"Aptos Display\", sans-serif; color: rgb(15, 71, 97); font-weight: normal;\'><br><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 20px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Final Summary</strong></span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 1.15;\"><span style=\"font-size: 18px; line-height: 115%; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Addressing the intricate and varied realm of blood cancers, hemato-oncology is a crucial and quickly developing field. Patients have every reason to be optimistic if they have access to accurate information, an early diagnosis, and a reliable specialist like&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size: 18px; line-height: 115%; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(44, 130, 201);\"><a href=\"https://drbadolacancercare.com/\"><strong>Dr. Amit Badola</strong></a></span><span style=\"font-size: 18px; line-height: 115%; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>.</strong> From state-of-the-art diagnostics to personalized&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size: 18px; line-height: 115%; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(44, 130, 201);\"><a href=\"https://drbadolacancercare.com/contact\"><strong>blood cancer treatment</strong></a></span><span style=\"font-size: 18px; line-height: 115%; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">&nbsp;strategies, the journey toward healing is more empowered than ever.</span></p>', 'blood-cancer-treatment');

